Quick installation instructions for VAMPS
==========================================

Requirements
------------
  - ANSI C compiler (gcc >= 4 or Apple clang)
  - GNU make
  - Python >= 3.9 with development headers (python3-config must be on PATH)
  - NumPy (pip install numpy)
  - termcap or ncurses (for interactive binary mode; optional for vampspy use)

On macOS (Homebrew):
  brew install python

On Debian/Ubuntu:
  apt install gcc make python3-dev


Source build
------------

1. Run configure to detect your platform and generate vconfig.h:

     cd src
     ./configure

   Optional: set CFLAGS for optimisation before configure:
     export CFLAGS="-O3 -ffast-math"    # typical flags; adjust for your compiler

2. Build the static libraries and binaries:

     make all

   This builds five libraries (libdef.a, libnru.a, libmaq.a, libts.a, libmet.a)
   into libDarwin_arm64/ (or the OS-appropriate sibling directory) and then
   compiles the two executables in src/:

     vamps  — main simulation binary
     vsel   — time-series extraction utility

3. Install system-wide (optional; requires write access to /usr/local):

     make install

   Or set PATH to include src/ for local use.

4. Set VAMPSLIB to point to the Python library files:

     export VAMPSLIB=/path/to/vamps/share
     # or, from the source tree:
     export VAMPSLIB=$(pwd)/share

5. Install the vampspy Python package (builds the _vampscore C extension):

     pip install -e .

   This compiles the entire C source tree with -DVAMPS_EXT_BUILD (which
   suppresses the standalone main() and dotail()) and links it into a
   Python extension module vampspy/_vampscore.so.


Quick test
----------

   cd examples/fiji
   vamps fiji.inp                  # binary test
   python fiji.py                  # vampspy Python test


Man pages
---------

   make man-install    (run from doc/)

   Or copy doc/man/vamps.1 and doc/man/vamps.5 to your man path manually.


Clean
-----

   make -C src clean          # remove object files
   make -C src distclean      # remove object files, libraries and vconfig.h

